Sections.Text:
By 2020, most people will be classified as middle class. In 2009, according to the OECD, North America accounted for 18% of the worlds middle-class population. As Asia grows, this is expected to drop to 7% by 2030, with the middle class in Asia Pacific due to surge to 66% of the global total, from just 28% in 2009.

 Asias consumer base is growing in size and in purchasing power, with demographic trends causing growth in consumer spending over the long-term. Spending may be under pressure for now, due to the slowdown in global growth, but the long-term trend remains. As Asian households move up the income ladder, spending in areas like travel, fashion, education, entertainment, and health and wellness will increase, presenting investment opportunities.

 Although this has been highlighted as a super trend, investing in emerging markets is not without risk. Emerging markets have high levels of dollar-denominated debt, making them susceptible to rising US interest rates and a stronger dollar. In addition, investing in emerging markets typically comes with a higher sovereign risk. Emerging market equities can also be more volatile than developed-market equities.

 The stocks and ETFs in this theme are large-cap companies, selected for their exposure to Asian consumer growth.
